    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the leaks are scattered across multiple modules, it's less like a single, fat, greedy beast and more like a swarm of tiny, mischievous little gnomes—each one stealing a crumb here and there. This is where you need to move from *where* the allocation happened to *what* the allocation was for.\n\nSince you have the allocation logs, you need to correlate the addresses with the *type* of object being allocated. If you're using C++ classes, try to augment your logging to capture the object's type information (e.g., the name of the class or struct). If you're using raw memory, you might need to use a custom memory pool or metadata header attached to each block to identify its intended purpose.\n\nIf you see several different stack traces, but they *all* allocate objects of the same type—say, `SensorReadingBuffer`—then you've found your pattern. The leak isn't necessarily one module; it's a common failure mode in how that specific object type is being managed across different parts of your system. This is often a failure in shared resource management, like a global cache or a poorly managed queue structure.",
